roject Gutenberg-tm collection will' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'remain freely available for generations to come.  In 2001, the Project' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation was created to provide a secure' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'and permanent future for Project Gutenberg-tm and future generations.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'To learn more about the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'and how your efforts and donations can help, see Sections 3 and 4' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'and the Foundation web page at http://www.pglaf.org.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Section 3.  Information about the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Foundation' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'The Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation is a non profit' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'501(c)(3) educational corporation organized under the laws of the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'state of Mississippi and granted tax exempt status by the Internal' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Revenue Service.  The Foundation''s EIN or federal tax identification' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'number is 64-6221541.  Its 501(c)(3) letter is posted at' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'http://pglaf.org/fundraising.  Contributions to the Project Gutenberg' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Literary Archive Foundation are tax deductible to the full extent' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'permitted by U.S. federal laws and your state''s laws.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'The Foundation''s principal office is located at 4557 Melan Dr. S.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Fairbanks, AK, 99712., but its volunteers and employees are scattered' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'throughout numerous locations.  Its business office is located at' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'809 North 1500 West, Salt Lake City, UT 84116, (801) 596-1887, email' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'business@pglaf.org.  Email contact links and up to date contact' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'information can be found at the Foundation''s web site and official' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'page at http://pglaf.org' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'For additional contact information:' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'     Dr. Gregory B. Newby' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'     Chief Executive and Director' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'     gbnewby@pglaf.org' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Section 4.  Information about Donations to the Project Gutenberg' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Literary Archive Foundation' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Project Gutenberg-tm depends upon and cannot survive without wide' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'spread public support and donations to carry out its mission of' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'increasing the number of public domain and licensed works that can be' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'freely distributed in machine readable form accessible by the widest' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'array of equipment including outdated equipment.  Many small donations' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'($1 to $5,000) are particularly important to maintaining tax exempt' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'status with the IRS.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'The Foundation is committed to complying with the laws regulating' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'charities and charitable donations in all 50 states of the United' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'States.  Compliance requirements are not uniform and it takes a' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'considerable effort, much paperwork and many fees to meet and keep up' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'with these requirements.  We do not solicit donations in locations' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'where we have not received written confirmation of compliance.  To' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'SEND DONATIONS or determine the status of compliance for any' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'particular state visit http://pglaf.org' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'While we cannot and do not solicit contributions from states where we' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'have not met the solicitation requirements, we know of no prohibition' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'against accepting unsolicited donations from donors in such states who' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'approach us with offers to donate.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'International donations are gratefully accepted, but we cannot make' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'any statements concerning tax treatment of donations received from' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'outside the United States.  U.S. laws alone swamp our small staff.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Please check the Project Gutenberg Web pages for current donation' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'methods and addresses.  Donations are accepted in a number of other' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'ways including checks, online payments and credit card donations.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'To donate, please visit: http://pglaf.org/donate' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Section 5.  General Information About Project Gutenberg-tm electronic' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'works.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Professor Michael S. Hart is the originator of the Project Gutenberg-tm' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'concept of a library of electronic works that could be freely shared' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'with anyone.  For thirty years, he produced and distributed Project' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Gutenberg-tm eBooks with only a loose network of volunteer support.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Project Gutenberg-tm eBooks are often created from several printed' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'editions, all of which are confirmed as Public Domain in the U.S.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'unless a copyright notice is included.  Thus, we do not necessarily' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'keep eBooks in compliance with any particular paper edition.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Most people start at our Web site which has the main PG search facility:' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'     http://www.gutenberg.org' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'This Web site includes information about Project Gutenberg-tm,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'including how to make donations to the Project Gutenberg Literary' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Archive Foundation, how to help produce our new eBooks, and how to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'subscribe to our email newsletter to hear about new eBooks.');
INSERT INTO notes (parent, permanent, expanded, created, icons, title, text) VALUES (104, 0, 1, '2008-11-27 16:32:38', 0, N'Chapter 61', N'Happy for all her maternal feelings was the day on which Mrs. Bennet got' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'rid of her two most deserving daughters. With what delighted pride' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'she afterwards visited Mrs. Bingley, and talked of Mrs. Darcy, may' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'be guessed. I wish I could say, for the sake of her family, that the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'accomplishment of her earnest desire in the establishment of so many' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of her children produced so happy an effect as to make her a sensible,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'amiable, well-informed woman for the rest of her life; though perhaps it' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'was lucky for her husband, who might not have relished domestic felicity' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'in so unusual a form, that she still was occasionally nervous and' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'invariably silly.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mr. Bennet missed his second daughter exceedingly; his affection for her' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'drew him oftener from home than anything else could do. He delighted in' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'going to Pemberley, especially when he was least expected.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mr. Bingley and Jane remained at Netherfield only a twelvemonth. So near' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'a vicinity to her mother and Meryton relations was not desirable even to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'_his_ easy temper, or _her_ affectionate heart. The darling wish of his' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'sisters was then gratified; he bought an estate in a neighbouring county' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'to Derbyshire, and Jane and Elizabeth, in addition to every other source' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of happiness, were within thirty miles of each other.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Kitty, to her very material advantage, spent the chief of her time with' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'her two elder sisters. In society so superior to what she had generally' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'known, her improvement was great. She was not of so ungovernable a' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'temper as Lydia; and, removed from the influence of Lydia''s example,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'she became, by proper attention and management, less irritable, less' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'ignorant, and less insipid. From the further disadvantage of Lydia''s' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'society she was of course carefully kept, and though Mrs. Wickham' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'frequently invited her to come and stay with her, with the promise of' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'balls and young men, her father would never consent to her going.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mary was the only daughter who remained at home; and she was necessarily' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'drawn from the pursuit of accomplishments by Mrs. Bennet''s being quite' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'unable to sit alone. Mary was obliged to mix more with the world, but' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'she could still moralize over every morning visit; and as she was no' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'longer mortified by comparisons between her sisters'' beauty and her own,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'it was suspected by her father that she submitted to the change without' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'much reluctance.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'As for Wickham and Lydia, their characters suffered no revolution from' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'the marriage of her sisters. He bore with philosophy the conviction that' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Elizabeth must now become acquainted with whatever of his ingratitude' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'and falsehood had before been unknown to her; and in spite of every' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'thing, was not wholly without hope that Darcy might yet be prevailed on' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'to make his fortune. The congratulatory letter which Elizabeth received' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'from Lydia on her marriage, explained to her that, by his wife at least,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'if not by himself, such a hope was cherished. The letter was to this' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'effect:' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"MY DEAR LIZZY,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I wish you joy. If you love Mr. Darcy half as well as I do my dear' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Wickham, you must be very happy. It is a great comfort to have you so' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'rich, and when you have nothing else to do, I hope you will think of us.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'I am sure Wickham would like a place at court very much, and I do not' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'think we shall have quite money enough to live upon without some help.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Any place would do, of about three or four hundred a year; but however,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'do not speak to Mr. Darcy about it, if you had rather not.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Yours, etc."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'As it happened that Elizabeth had _much_ rather not, she endeavoured in' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'her answer to put an end to every entreaty and expectation of the kind.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Such relief, however, as it was in her power to afford, by the practice' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of what might be called economy in her own private expences, she' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'frequently sent them. It had always been evident to her that such an' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'income as theirs, under the direction of two persons so extravagant in' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'their wants, and heedless of the future, must be very insufficient to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'their support; and whenever they changed their quarters, either Jane or' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'herself were sure of being applied to for some little assistance' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'towards discharging their bills. Their manner of living, even when the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'restoration of peace dismissed them to a home, was unsettled in the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'extreme. They were always moving from place to place in quest of a cheap' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'situation, and always spending more than they ought. His affection for' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'her soon sunk into indifference; her''s lasted a little longer; and' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'in spite of her youth and her manners, she retained all the claims to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'reputation which her marriage had given her.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Though Darcy could never receive _him_ at Pemberley, yet, for' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Elizabeth''s sake, he assisted him further in his profession. Lydia was' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'occasionally a visitor there, when her husband was gone to enjoy himself' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'in London or Bath; and with the Bingleys they both of them frequently' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'staid so long, that even Bingley''s good humour was overcome, and he' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'proceeded so far as to talk of giving them a hint to be gone.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Miss Bingley was very deeply mortified by Darcy''s marriage; but as she' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'thought it advisable to retain the right of visiting at Pemberley, she' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'dropt all her resentment; was fonder than ever of Georgiana, almost as' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'attentive to Darcy as heretofore, and paid off every arrear of civility' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'to Elizabeth.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Pemberley was now Georgiana''s home; and the attachment of the sisters' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'was exactly what Darcy had hoped to see. They were able to love each' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'other even as well as they intended. Georgiana had the highest opinion' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'in the world of Elizabeth; though at first she often listened with' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'an astonishment bordering on alarm at her lively, sportive, manner of' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'talking to her brother. He, who had always inspired in herself a respect' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'which almost overcame her affection, she now saw the object of open' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'pleasantry. Her mind received knowledge which had never before fallen' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'in her way. By Elizabeth''s instructions, she began to comprehend that' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'a woman may take liberties with her husband which a brother will not' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'always allow in a sister more than ten years younger than himself.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Lady Catherine was extremely indignant on the marriage of her nephew;' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'and as she gave way to all the genuine frankness of her character in' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'her reply to the letter which announced its arrangement, she sent him' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'language so very abusive, especially of Elizabeth, that for some time' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'all intercourse was at an end. But at length, by Elizabeth''s persuasion,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'he was prevailed on to overlook the offence, and seek a reconciliation;' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'and, after a little further resistance on the part of his aunt, her' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'resentment gave way, either to her affection for him, or her curiosity' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'to see how his wife conducted herself; and she condescended to wait' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'on them at Pemberley, in spite of that pollution which its woods had' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'received, not merely from the presence of such a mistress, but the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'visits of her uncle and aunt from the city.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'With the Gardiners, they were always on the most intimate terms.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Darcy, as well as Elizabeth, really loved them; and they were both ever' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'sensible of the warmest gratitude towards the persons who, by bringing' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'her into Derbyshire, had been the means of uniting them.');
